"application/json\")\n\tw.WriteHeader(http.StatusNotFound)\n\tjson.NewEncoder(w).Encode(map[string]string{\"error\": \"project not found\"})\n\treturn \"\", \"\", false\n}\n","numLines":25,"startLine":810,"totalLines":1301}}}
[2026-03-08T04:13:30Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01HL3YRA86WyXCetJGjv1KkN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the information I need. Here's my plan:\n\n1. **Routes** in `handler.go`:\n   - Add `GET /projects/{name}/runs` → `handleProjectRunsList` (new HTML handler)\n   - Add `GET /api/projects/{name}/runs` → `handleAPIProjectRuns` (new API handler)\n   - Keep `GET /runs` for listing all runs (no project filter), but remove the project filter query param support\n   - Keep `GET /api/runs` for listing all runs\n\n2. **New handlers** in `handler.go`:\n   - `handleProjectRunsList` - resolves project name, lists runs for that project, renders template\n   - `handleAPIProjectRuns` - resolves project name, lists runs for that project, returns JSON\n\n3. **Templates**:\n   - `projects.html` and `project_detail.html`: Update the run list links to use the new `/projects/{label}/runs` path\n   - `runs.html`: Adjust the filter navigation and API polling to work with the new project-scoped routes\n   - `run_detail.html`: Update the back link accordingly\n\nFor the runs page itself, I need to think through the routing more carefully. The `/runs` endpoint should continue showing all runs without filtering, while `/projects/{name}/runs` displays runs scoped to that specific project. Rather than duplicating template logic, I can have both routes render the same template but with different data contexts—the general runs handler stays as-is, and a new project-specific handler resolves the project directory and pre-populates the filtered view.\n\nThe template's dropdown navigation needs updating too. Currently it navigates using `?project=` query parameters with directory paths, but the new structure should use `/projects/{label}/runs` URLs instead. Since the dropdown values are directory paths and URLs need labels, I'll need to adjust how the template constructs these navigation links to use the project labels rather than raw directory names. I'm updating the dropdown options to store both the directory and label, then modifying the filter function to navigate using the label-based URL structure instead of the directory path. For the API polling, I need to pass the project label to the template so it can call the correct endpoint.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the handler structure: one for the general runs page that polls `/api/runs`, and another for project-specific runs that polls `/api/projects/{label}/runs`. I'll add the `ProjectLabel` field to the template data so the JavaScript can construct the right API URL, then implement the new routes and handlers to support this filtering.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":432,"cache_read_input_tokens":32468,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":432},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c4dcaef6-cf2e-409b-9a28-740c6f4b681e","uuid":"1316faf6-4e72-4239-802e-831bfb97f705"}
